It's pretty much the best restaurant I've been to in my life. There you go.

I was looking forward to another superlative Danko experience this week, and sadly I was disappointed. We had made reservations over a month in advance, and we arrived slightly early and made our presence known, but we still had to stand waiting for over 20 minutes past our reservation time in a crowded and uncomfortable entrance in order to escape the inclement weather. As you may know, the sale of foie gras will be illegal in Concentration Camp California come summer. For this reason this was supposed to be my swan song, pardon the partial pun. Unfortunately it was, but not in a positive sense. On a past visit, I ordered badly and my companion ordered very well. He had the risotto (creamy cheese perfection), the foie gras stuffed quail (heavenly), and a dessert I don't remember. I had the oysters with caviar in a frothy broth (too bland and small), a fish dish I recall as being mediocre, and a dessert that was nice, although I don't recall the name. On our visit this week he again had the risotto and it was again divine. For my appetizer I had the foie gras portion which was served in a very nice glaze but unfortunately the foie gras was not of excellent quality. It was fresh, but it lacked the rich fat content and subtle delicacy that distinguishes a truly fine liver. He also ordered the quail, as did I. Unfortunately this time it was more Whole Foods quality than Michelin starred restaurant. While tasty, the quail was a bit salty and primarily stuffed with mushrooms and quinoa. Where was the former, positively oozing, foie gras deliciousness? So sad. :( We both had the chocolate souffle, which was average at best. There's Souffle Cafe in Chinatown that would give Danko a run for their money in this department, although the service at Danko's is much nicer. I should also add that the free tasting bite they gave us shortly after seating was one of the best things in the restaurant, other than the wine and risotto. It was salmon in a lovely avocado and sesame preparation that was somewhat like an Asian fish tartare dish. The service was good, as always, other than the long wait, but overall the restaurant was not worth of the price or reputation on our visit this week. Unless I have a client who insists on going (and paying) I may not be back.

Yikes. From the first step through the door, I was not feeling Gary Danko. The ambience is straight out of 1994 - dark wall coverings, tall irises in gilded vases, marble rolling cheese cart. The restaurant was also packed with tourists who were recording every moment of their meal with flash photography. I found the food to be dated and disappointing given the high price point. I'll describe a few items off the menu to illustrate my opinion. The amuse bouche was a slice of ham with a forgettable liquid on the side and a few sliced green onions. It tasted like a straight up piece of lunch meat. My husband's crab salad... First of all, the availability of Dungeness Crab way out of season just shows you how tourist-focused this place is. The salad was made with avocado and roasted bell pepper (?) mayonnaise. Seriously. It was reminiscent of a salad that comes in a plastic tub at Safeway. My sea scallops were succulent, but were missing a good crusty sear. It was paired with a potato puree' and TOMATO SAUCE. I was shaking my head at this point. My pork two ways (belly and loin) was delicious; however, it was paired with frisee (hellooooo 1990) and PICKLED JALAPENOS straight out of the jar. The flavors did not mesh at all. At this stage we decided to drop the last course and just finish off with a selection of cheeses, which were good. Tough to really screw up cheese, particularly when none are made in-house. They were matched, very uncreatively, with some grapes and bread. We were then given a little passionfruit cheesecake to share for our anniversary. IT WAS FROZEN IN THE MIDDLE. Service was okay. We did appreciate a glass of wine on the house as an apology for the relentless flash photography and toddlers seated next to us. Danko is also famous for its little "take home" gift... Which apparently they were running low on, because as a couple we were only given one little package... Pretty bizarre considering we were dropping $300 on dinner. It was banana bread with cream cheese frosting, and it was totally run-of-the-mill. This experience was completely and thoroughly mediocre. There was nothing innovative on my plate, and nothing which honored the seasonal, local, or organic flavors which we are so lucky to have an abundance here in Northern California. I will definitely never go back considering the other options available to me.

0 star - for the seating time. They did not seat us until pass our reservation time, even when the seats are available. (I know, you want me to spend at your bar - but I am here only for the food) 0 star - atmosphere. This place is too packed and noisy for my anniversary dinner. I can hear clearly every word the tables around me (which were 1 feet away from our table) 0 star - the bread is worse than my 1-week sourdough at home. 1 star - flexibility of the menu. I ordered two seafood + 1 entree for a 3-course price. 1 star - for decent food. They meet my fine dining expectations, but I do not crave for any dish afterwards. 1 star - complimentary anniversary lemon cheesecake. (As long as you book your reservation and name an occasion, they will give you one) 1 star - complimentary desserts. Actually I did miss this afterwards! 0 star - for service. I think they just did OK. I cannot say attentive. So... my math says 4-stars, which is about right. Coming here once is good enough for me.

I'll try to say things that others might not have said (not that I am going to read through 2000 reviews). Last time I went, my good friend made reservations but when we arrived, the hostess couldn't find them. So why am I not taking one star off for this hiccup? Because THEY SEATED US ANYWAY. How crazy is that? I am sure a million other folks have tried the "no really, I made reservations with you" ploy to get into GD when they are lying through their teeth. Perhaps it was the crushed look on my face and tears welling up in my eyes that convinced the hostess. I love the little touches--the purse hooks for lady's bags, the bread and butter server who appears whenever I have just one bite left on the bread plate. The servers who always make me feel as though I am the most important/funniest/charming guest they've had all evening. The breakfast bread for the women at the end of the meal. (I don't think men get the parting gift, but am willing to be corrected. Certainly my boyfriend didn't when we went together). The amuse bouche to whet the appetite. I routinely get the 5-course menu, and I never order dessert anymore, because I know the plate of mouth size morsels is coming with my coffee. Plus, if you say it's a special occasion when you make your ressie, you'll get a free dessert for your birthday or anniversary. Last time I went, we were given a passionfruit cheesecake type thing, with each bite devine. I also don't get dessert because as I've aged I prefer "fat" rather than "sweet". The food! My god, it's delicious. The crispy fried egg has to be eaten to be believed. As the egg is being poached, it's being formed into an oval. It is then rolled in panko or something similar and quickly deep fried. Served over frisee with varying "set up"-- it is one of the most perfect dishes I've ever had. The menu "changes" four times a year, per the season. My goal this year is to experience each seasonal menu (and I just have one more to go). The main focus of each dish stays the same throughout the year; it's the set up around the food that will change. So, you can expect to have a (delicious!!!) risotto with lobster and rock shrimp on the menu, but depending on the time of year you may have butternut squash in the risotto, or asparagus, or peas. You'll always have a beef filet offered, but perhaps with spaetzle versus potatoes. I actually find GD's prices for the food to be quite reasonable for what you get. A 5-course menu (culled from what--40 options?--of anything I want--5 appetizers, 5 seafoods, or 5 desserts, WHATEVER I want), 5 courses of food of this quality for $105 per person? That's a bargain! I've had some lovely glasses of wine very reasonably priced. (I've also had 2 glasses of a French champagne they recommended at $28 a glass--whoopsee!!). How many times have you gone to a "good" restaurant, paid $100 for dinner, drinks and tip for two, and left feeling the experience was sub par? Happens to my boyfriend and me routinely. Experience that three times a year, and there's the cost of dinner for two at GD. So price, it's worth it, end of story.

I get a lot of grief from other chefs in San Francisco when I tell them that I'm going to eat at RGD. They say it's overrated and that the food is ten years behind the current trends, but when I comes down to it they are just jealous that their restaurants can't execute on a high level consistently like RGD. Let's face it 99% of people don't know the intricacies of the seasonal and trendy culinary world, but 100% of people can tell when they are getting elite unpretentious service that is making them feel as if they are special and the value for the experience is there. The food was good, but the service is unparalleled!

Unfortunately this time it was more Whole Foods quality than Michelin starred restaurant. While tasty, the quail was a bit salty and primarily stuffed with mushrooms and quinoa. Where was the former, positively oozing, foie gras deliciousness? So sad. :(

    We both had the chocolate souffle, which was average at best. There's Souffle Cafe in Chinatown that would give Danko a run for their money in this department, although the service at Danko's is much nicer.

    I should also add that the free tasting bite they gave us shortly after seating was one of the best things in the restaurant, other than the wine and risotto. It was salmon in a lovely avocado and sesame preparation that was somewhat like an Asian fish tartare dish.

    The service was good, as always, other than the long wait, but overall the restaurant was not worth of the price or reputation on our visit this week.

    Unless I have a client who insists on going (and paying) I may not be back.

    9/13/2010

    Yikes.

    From the first step through the door, I was not feeling Gary Danko. The ambience is straight out of 1994 - dark wall coverings, tall irises in gilded vases, marble rolling cheese cart. The restaurant was also packed with tourists who were recording every moment of their meal with flash photography.

    I found the food to be dated and disappointing given the high price point. I'll describe a few items off the menu to illustrate my opinion.

    The amuse bouche was a slice of ham with a forgettable liquid on the side and a few sliced green onions. It tasted like a straight up piece of lunch meat.

    My husband's crab salad... First of all, the availability of Dungeness Crab way out of season just shows you how tourist-focused this place is. The salad was made with avocado and roasted bell pepper (?) mayonnaise. Seriously. It was reminiscent of a salad that comes in a plastic tub at Safeway.

    My sea scallops were succulent, but were missing a good crusty sear. It was paired with a potato puree' and TOMATO SAUCE. I was shaking my head at this point.

    My pork two ways (belly and loin) was delicious; however, it was paired with frisee (hellooooo 1990) and PICKLED JALAPENOS straight out of the jar. The flavors did not mesh at all.

    At this stage we decided to drop the last course and just finish off with a selection of cheeses, which were good. Tough to really screw up cheese, particularly when none are made in-house. They were matched, very uncreatively, with some grapes and bread.  

    We were then given a little passionfruit cheesecake to share for our anniversary. IT WAS FROZEN IN THE MIDDLE.

    Service was okay. We did appreciate a glass of wine on the house as an apology for the relentless flash photography and toddlers seated next to us.

    Danko is also famous for its little "take home" gift... Which apparently they were running low on, because as a couple we were only given one little package... Pretty bizarre considering we were dropping $300 on dinner. It was banana bread with cream cheese frosting, and it was totally run-of-the-mill.

    This experience was completely and thoroughly mediocre. There was nothing innovative on my plate, and nothing which honored the seasonal, local, or organic flavors which we are so lucky to have an abundance here in Northern California. I will definitely never go back considering the other options available to me.

    11/7/2010

    I'll try to say things that others might not have said (not that I am going to read through 2000 reviews).

    Last time I went, my good friend made reservations but when we arrived, the hostess couldn't find them.  So why am I not taking one star off for this hiccup?  Because THEY SEATED US ANYWAY.  How crazy is that?  I am sure a million other folks have tried the "no really, I made reservations with you" ploy to get into GD when they are lying through their teeth.  Perhaps it was the crushed look on my face and tears welling up in my eyes that convinced the hostess.

    I love the little touches--the purse hooks for lady's bags, the bread and butter server who appears whenever I have just one bite left on the bread plate.  The servers who always make me feel as though I am the most important/funniest/charming guest they've had all evening.  The breakfast bread for the women at the end of the meal.  (I don't think men get the parting gift, but am willing to be corrected. Certainly my boyfriend didn't when we went together).  The amuse bouche to whet the appetite.

    I routinely get the 5-course menu, and I never order dessert anymore, because I know the plate of mouth size morsels is coming with my coffee.  Plus, if you say it's a special occasion when you make your ressie, you'll get a free dessert for your birthday or anniversary.  Last time I went, we were given a passionfruit cheesecake type thing, with each bite devine.  I also don't get dessert because as I've aged I prefer "fat" rather than "sweet".

    The food!  My god, it's delicious.  The crispy fried egg has to be eaten to be believed.  As the egg is being poached, it's being formed into an oval.  It is then rolled in panko or something similar and quickly deep fried.  Served over frisee with varying "set up"-- it is one of the most perfect dishes I've ever had.  

    The menu "changes" four times a year, per the season.  My goal this year is to experience each seasonal menu (and I just have one more to go).  The main focus of each dish stays the same throughout the year; it's the set up around the food that will change.  So, you can expect to have a (delicious!!!) risotto with lobster and rock shrimp on the menu, but depending on the time of year you may have butternut squash in the risotto, or asparagus, or peas.  You'll always have a beef filet offered, but perhaps with spaetzle versus potatoes.  

    I actually find GD's prices for the food to be quite reasonable for what you get.  A 5-course menu (culled from what--40 options?--of anything I want--5 appetizers, 5 seafoods, or 5 desserts, WHATEVER I want), 5 courses of food of this quality for $105 per person?  That's a bargain!  I've had some lovely glasses of wine very reasonably priced.  (I've also had 2 glasses of a French champagne they recommended at $28 a glass--whoopsee!!).  How many times have you gone to a "good" restaurant, paid $100 for dinner, drinks and tip for two, and left feeling the experience was sub par?  Happens to my boyfriend and me routinely.  Experience that three times a year, and there's the cost of dinner for two at GD.  So price, it's worth it, end of story.
